        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will use 4 spectral windows, each of width 1875 MHz, and with center rest frequencies of 331.23, 333.15, 343.374, &amp; 345.23 GHz. This will allow us to center the 12CO (as well as the 13CO J=3-2 line, that we may detect depending on the unknown 12C/13C ratio in the central region) sufficiently far from the bandpass edge. We have set the 2 continuum SPWs to 31.25 MHz resolution, since these are primarily for detecting continuum emission. For the SPWs at 345.23 that include the 12CO line, that is our main probe, we request 468.75 MHz bandwidth and 0.212 km/s velocity resolution. For 13CO, that is likely to be much weaker, we request 937.5 MHz bandwidth and 0.442 km/s velocity resolution.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Given the disk size of 0.6" in the near and mid-IR, we will to need to cover a minimum field-of-view of 2 arcsec, which requires two pointings, and we need about 0.1" resolution to adequately resolve the disk and its spatio-kinematic structure.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The main objective is to map the 12COJ=3-2 line in V Hya (and the 0.87 mm continuum), with an angular resolution of 0.1". We have used the observed SMA CO 3-2 observations of V Hya by Hirano et al (2004) with beam-sizes of 3.1" x 1.9", to estimate an expected flux of about 30 mJy in the CO J=3-2 line and about 1 mJy in the continuum per 0.1"x0.1" beam element, in the central region. We will therefore aim for an rms sensitivity of 3 mJy at 0.35 km/s velocity resolution to probe the disk for the signature of rotation and determine the rotation curve. This will require an on-source integration time of 1.48 hours, and provide a peak S/N ratio of 10 in the line. We will get a S/N ratio &gt;38 in the continuum. Given the disk size of 0.6" in the near and mid-IR, we will to need to cover a minimum field-of-view of 2 arcsec, which requires two pointings.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our data rate, 12.61 MB/s, is just slightly above the policyr value of 12.0 MB/s. However, it is necessary as we need to image the 12CO3-2 line at high spectral resolution in order to look for the signature of rotation.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
