    <prp:abstract>The carbon star V Hya is experiencing heavy mass loss as it undergoes the transition from an AGB star to a bipolar pre-planetary nebula, and is possibly the earliest object known in this brief phase, which is so short that few nearby stars are likely to be caught in the act. Our STIS/HST data showed a high velocity (&gt;200 km/s) knotty outflow that was ejected very recently from the star. SMA CO observations with ~3.5" resolution also revealed an extended high-velocity, collimated outflow (aligned E-W) and a N-S elongated dense waist (size 8" in CO 3-2). We recently obtained coronagraphic polarimetric imaging with GPI at 1 micron to directly image an inclined disk of size 0.6" (or 240 AU) at the center of the waist. We propose to observe the CO J=3-2 line and 0.87 mm dust continuum at 0.1" resolution in V Hya to determine whether this disk is in rotation or in expansion, and constrain its mass. These observations of V Hya offer us an unprecedented opportunity to investigate the disk that is the launch-site of the jet-like outflows that produce bipolar planetary nebulae, and test models for making such disks, such as accretion onto a companion or common-envelope ejection.</prp:abstract>
